#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:5
msgid "NumPy benchmarks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:7
msgid "Benchmarking NumPy with Airspeed Velocity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:11
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:13
msgid ""
"Airspeed Velocity manages building and Python virtualenvs by itself, unless "
"told otherwise. To run the benchmarks, you do not need to install a "
"development version of NumPy to your current Python environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:17
msgid ""
"Before beginning, ensure that *airspeed velocity* is installed. By default, "
"`asv` ships with support for anaconda and virtualenv::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:20
msgid ""
"pip install asv\n"
"pip install virtualenv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:23
msgid ""
"After contributing new benchmarks, you should test them locally before "
"submitting a pull request."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:26
msgid ""
"To run all benchmarks, navigate to the root NumPy directory at the command "
"line and execute::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:29
msgid "spin bench"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:31
msgid ""
"This builds NumPy and runs all available benchmarks defined in ``benchmarks/"
"``. (Note: this could take a while. Each benchmark is run multiple times to "
"measure the distribution in execution times.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:36
msgid ""
"For **testing** benchmarks locally, it may be better to run these without "
"replications::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:39
msgid ""
"cd benchmarks/\n"
"export REGEXP=\"bench.*Ufunc\"\n"
"asv run --dry-run --show-stderr --python=same --quick -b $REGEXP"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:43
msgid ""
"Where the regular expression used to match benchmarks is stored in "
"``$REGEXP``, and `--quick` is used to avoid repetitions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:46
msgid ""
"To run benchmarks from a particular benchmark module, such as ``bench_core."
"py``, simply append the filename without the extension::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:49
msgid "spin bench -t bench_core"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:51
msgid ""
"To run a benchmark defined in a class, such as ``MeshGrid`` from "
"``bench_creation.py``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:54
msgid "spin bench -t bench_creation.MeshGrid"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:56
msgid ""
"Compare changes in benchmark results to another version/commit/branch, use "
"the ``--compare`` option (or the equivalent ``-c``)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:59
msgid ""
"spin bench --compare v1.6.2 -t bench_core\n"
"spin bench --compare 20d03bcfd -t bench_core\n"
"spin bench -c main -t bench_core"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:63
msgid ""
"All of the commands above display the results in plain text in the console, "
"and the results are not saved for comparison with future commits. For "
"greater control, a graphical view, and to have results saved for future "
"comparison you can run ASV commands (record results and generate HTML)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:69
msgid ""
"cd benchmarks\n"
"asv run -n -e --python=same\n"
"asv publish\n"
"asv preview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:74
msgid ""
"More on how to use ``asv`` can be found in `ASV documentation`_ Command-line "
"help is available as usual via ``asv --help`` and ``asv run --help``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:81
msgid "Benchmarking versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:83
msgid ""
"To benchmark or visualize only releases on different machines locally, the "
"tags with their commits can be generated, before being run with ``asv``, "
"that is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:85
msgid ""
"cd benchmarks\n"
"# Get commits for tags\n"
"# delete tag_commits.txt before re-runs\n"
"for gtag in $(git tag --list --sort taggerdate | grep \"^v\"); do\n"
"git log $gtag --oneline -n1 --decorate=no | awk '{print $1;}' >> tag_commits."
"txt\n"
"done\n"
"# Use the last 20\n"
"tail --lines=20 tag_commits.txt > 20_vers.txt\n"
"asv run HASHFILE:20_vers.txt\n"
"# Publish and view\n"
"asv publish\n"
"asv preview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:98
msgid ""
"For details on contributing these, see the `benchmark results repository`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:103
msgid "Writing benchmarks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:105
msgid "See `ASV documentation`_ for basics on how to write benchmarks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:107
msgid "Some things to consider:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:109
msgid "The benchmark suite should be importable with any NumPy version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:111
msgid ""
"The benchmark parameters etc. should not depend on which NumPy version is "
"installed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:114
msgid "Try to keep the runtime of the benchmark reasonable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:116
msgid ""
"Prefer ASV's ``time_`` methods for benchmarking times rather than cooking up "
"time measurements via ``time.clock``, even if it requires some juggling when "
"writing the benchmark."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:120
msgid ""
"Preparing arrays etc. should generally be put in the ``setup`` method rather "
"than the ``time_`` methods, to avoid counting preparation time together with "
"the time of the benchmarked operation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../benchmarks/README.rst:124
msgid ""
"Be mindful that large arrays created with ``np.empty`` or ``np.zeros`` might "
"not be allocated in physical memory until the memory is accessed. If this is "
"desired behaviour, make sure to comment it in your setup function. If you "
"are benchmarking an algorithm, it is unlikely that a user will be executing "
"said algorithm on a newly created empty/zero array. One can force pagefaults "
"to occur in the setup phase either by calling ``np.ones`` or ``arr."
"fill(value)`` after creating the array."
msgstr ""
